# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: snort-ids
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Traditional inspection technologies are unable to keep up with the recent outbreaks of widespread attacks.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] If this reconstruction and comprehension can be done in real-time, then real-time policies can be applied to traffic, preventing the propagation of malware, spam and valuable data loss.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Further, with DCI, the correlation and comprehension of the digital objects transmitted in many communication sessions leads to new ways of network performance optimization and intelligence regardless of protocol or blended communication sessions.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Historically, DPI was developed to detect and prevent intrusion.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] It was then used to provide Quality of Service where the flow of network traffic can be prioritized such that latency-sensitive traffic types (e.g., Voice over IP) can be utilized to provide higher flow priority.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] However, the detection and prevention of a new generation of malware such as Conficker and Stuxnet is only possible through the exhaustive analysis provided by DCI.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] As networks evolve, inspection techniques evolve; all attempting to understand the payload.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Historically, inspection technology examined only the IP Header and the TCP/UDP Header.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Dubbed as ‘Packet Filtering’, these devices would drop sequence packets, or packets that are not allowed on a network.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This scheme of network traffic inspection was first used by firewalls to protect against packet attacks.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Stateful packet inspection was developed to examine header information and the packet content to increase source and destination understanding.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Instead of letting the packets through as a result of their addresses and ports, packets stayed on the network if the context was appropriate to the networks’ current ‘state’.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This scheme was first used by Check Point firewalls and eventually Intrusion Prevention/Detection Systems.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Deep packet inspection is the predominant inspection tool used to analyze data packets passing through the network, including the headers and the data protocol structures.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] These technologies scan packet streams and look for offending patterns.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] To be effective, Deep Packet Inspection Systems must ‘string’ match Packet Payloads to malware signatures and specification signatures (which dictate what the request/response should be like) at wire speeds.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] To do so, FPGAs, or Field Programmable Gate Arrays, Network Processors, or even Graphics Processing Units (GPUs) are programmed to be hardwired with these signatures and, as a result, traffic that passes through such circuitry is quickly matched.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Parallel to the development of Deep Packet Inspection, the beginnings of Deep Content Inspection can be traced back as early as 1995 with the introduction of proxies that stopped malware or spam.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Proxies have been deployed to provide internet caching services to retrieve objects and then forward them.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Consequently, all network traffic is intercepted, and potentially stored.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] These graduated to what is now known as secure web gateways, proxy-based inspections retrieve and scans object, script, and images.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Proxies, which relies on a fetch the content first if it were not cached, then forwarding the content to the recipient introduced some form of file inspection as early as 1995 when MAILsweeper was released by Content Technologies (now Clearswift), which was then replaced by MIMEsweeper in 2005.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] 2006 saw the release of the open-source, cross-platform antivirus software ClamAV provided support for caching proxies, Squid and NetCache.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Using the Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP), a proxy will pass the downloaded content for scanning to an ICAP server running an anti-virus software.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Since complete files or ‘objects’ were passed for scanning, proxy-based anti-virus solutions are considered the first generation of network content inspection.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] BlueCoat, WebWasher and Secure Computing Inc.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] (now McAfee, now a division of Intel), provided commercial implementations of proxies, eventually becoming a standard network element in most enterprise networks.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] The Second generation of Network Traffic Inspection solutions were implemented in firewalls and/or UTMs.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Given that network traffic is choked through these devices, in addition to DPI inspection, proxy-like inspection is possible.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This approach was first pioneered by NetScreen Technologies Inc.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] However, given the expensive cost of such operation, this feature was applied in tandem with a DPI system and was only activated on a-per-need basis, or when content failed to be qualified through the DPI system.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] The third, and current, generation of network content inspection, known as deep content inspection solutions, are implemented as fully transparent devices that perform full application level content inspection at wire speed.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] In order to understand the communication session's intent —in its entirety—, a Deep Content Inspection System must scan both the handshake and payload.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Once the digital objects (executables, images, JavaScript's, .pdfs, etc. also referred to as Data-In-Motion) carried within the payload are constructed, usability, compliance and threat analysis of this session and its payload can be achieved.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Given that the handshake sequence and complete payload of the session is available to the DCI system, unlike DPI systems where simple pattern matching and reputation search are only possible, exhaustive object analysis is possible.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] The inspection provided by DCI systems can include signature matching, behavioral analysis, regulatory and compliance analysis, and correlation of the session under inspection to the history of previous sessions.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This third generation approach of deep content inspection was developed within the defence and intelligence community, first appearing in guard products such as SyBard, and later by Wedge Networks Inc..
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Deep content inspection is content-focused instead of analyzing packets or classifying traffic based on application types such as in Next Generation Firewalls.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] "Understanding" content and its intent is the highest level of intelligence to be gained from network traffic.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This is important as information flow is moving away from packet, towards application, and ultimately to content.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] DCI is currently being adopted by enterprises, service providers and governments as a reaction to increasingly complex internet traffic with the benefits of understanding complete file types and their intent.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Typically, these organizations have mission-critical applications with rigid requirements.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] This type of inspection deals with real time protocols that only continue to increase in complexity and size.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] One of the key barriers for providing this level of inspection, that is looking at all content, is dealing with network throughput.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Solutions must overcome this issue while not introducing latency into the network environment.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] They must also be able to effectively scale up to meet tomorrow's demands and the demands envisioned by the growing Cloud Computing trend.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] One approach is to use selective scanning; however, to avoid compromising accuracy, the selection criteria should be based on recurrence.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] The following patent USPTO# 7,630,379 provides a scheme as to how deep content inspection can be carried out effectively using a recurrence selection scheme.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] The novelty introduced by this patent is that it addresses issues such as content (E.g., an mp3 file) that could have been renamed before transmission.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Dealing with the amount of traffic and information and then applying services requires very high speed look ups to be able to be effective.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] Need to compare against full services platforms or else having all traffic is not being utilized effectively.
[src:snort-ids/deep-content-inspection] An example is often found in dealing with Viruses and Malicious content where solutions only compare content against a small virus database instead of a full and complete one.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS focuses on more granular and internal attacks through focusing monitoring host activities instead of overall network traffic.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] HIDS was the first type of intrusion detection software to have been designed, with the original target system being the mainframe computer where outside interaction was infrequent.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One major issue with using HIDS is that it needs to be installed on each and every computer that needs protection from intrusions.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This can lead to a slowdown in device performance and intrusion detection systems.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A host-based IDS is capable of monitoring all or parts of the dynamic behavior and the state of a computer system, based on how it is configured.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly a HIDS might look at the state of a system, its stored information, whether in RAM, in the file system, log files or elsewhere; and check that the contents of these appear as expected, e.g. have not been changed by intruders.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One can think of a HIDS as an agent that monitors whether anything or anyone, whether internal or external, has circumvented the system's security policy.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In comparison to network-based intrusion detection systems, HIDS is advantageous because of its capability of identifying internal attacks.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While NIDS examines data from network traffic, HIDS examines data originating from operating systems.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In recent years, HIDS has been faced with the big data challenge, which can be attributed to the increased advancement of data center facilities and methodologies.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many computer users have encountered tools that monitor dynamic system behavior in the form of anti-virus (AV) packages.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] While AV programs often also monitor system state, they do spend a lot of their time looking at who is doing what inside a computer – and whether a given program should or should not have access to particular system resources.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The lines become blurred here, as many of the tools overlap in functionality.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Some intrusion prevention systems protect against buffer overflow attacks on system memory and can enforce security policy.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] The principle operation of a HIDS depends on the fact that successful intruders (hackers) will generally leave a trace of their activities.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In theory, a computer user has the ability to detect any such modifications, and the HIDS attempts to do just that and reports its findings.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Ideally a HIDS works in conjunction with a NIDS, such that a HIDS finds anything that slips past the NIDS.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Commercially available software solutions often do correlate the findings from NIDS and HIDS in order to find out about whether a network intruder has been successful or not at the targeted host.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Most successful intruders, on entering a target machine, immediately apply best-practice security techniques to secure the system which they have infiltrated, leaving only their own backdoor open, so that other intruders can not take over *their* computers.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] In general a HIDS uses a database (object-database) of system objects it should monitor – usually (but not necessarily) file system objects.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS could also check that appropriate regions of memory have not been modified – for example, the system call table for Linux, and various vtable structures in Microsoft Windows.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] For each object in question a HIDS will usually remember its attributes (permissions, size, modifications dates) and create a checksum of some kind (an MD5, SHA1 hash or similar) for the contents, if any.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] This information gets stored in a secure database for later comparison (checksum database).
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] An alternate method to HIDS would be to provide NIDS type functionality at the network interface (NIC) level of an end-point (either server, workstation or other end device).
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Providing HIDS at the network layer has the advantage of providing more detailed logging of the source (IP address) of the attack and attack details, such as packet data, neither of which a dynamic behavioral monitoring approach could see.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] At installation time – and whenever any of the monitored objects change legitimately – a HIDS must initialize its checksum-database by scanning the relevant objects.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Persons in charge of computer security need to control this process tightly in order to prevent intruders making un-authorized changes to the database(s).
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Such initialization thus generally takes a long time and involves cryptographically locking each monitored object and the checksum databases or worse.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Because of this, manufacturers of HIDS usually construct the object-database in such a way that makes frequent updates to the checksum database unnecessary.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Computer systems generally have many dynamic (frequently changing) objects which intruders want to modify – and which a HIDS thus should monitor – but their dynamic nature makes them unsuitable for the checksum technique.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] To overcome this problem, HIDS employ various other detection techniques: monitoring changing file-attributes, log-files that decreased in size since last checked, and numerous other means to detect unusual events.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Reports can take the form of logs, e-mails or similar.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS will usually go to great lengths to prevent the object-database, checksum-database and its reports from any form of tampering.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] After all, if intruders succeed in modifying any of the objects the HIDS monitors, nothing can stop such intruders from modifying the HIDS itself – unless security administrators take appropriate precautions.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Many worms and viruses will try to disable anti-virus tools, for example.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Apart from crypto-techniques, HIDS might allow administrators to store the databases on a CD-ROM or on other read-only memory devices (another factor in favor of infrequent updates...) or storing them in some off-system memory.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Similarly, a HIDS will often send its logs off-system immediately – typically using VPN channels to some central management system.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] One could argue that the trusted platform module comprises a type of HIDS.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Although its scope differs in many ways from that of a HIDS, fundamentally it provides a means to identify whether anything/anyone has tampered with a portion of a computer.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] Architecturally this provides the ultimate (at least at this point in time) host-based intrusion detection, as depends on hardware external to the CPU itself, thus making it that much harder for an intruder to corrupt its object and checksum databases.
[src:snort-ids/host-based-intrusion-detection-system] InfoWorld states that host-based intrusion-detection system software is a useful way for network managers to find malware, and suggest they run it on every server, not just critical servers.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An **intrusion detection system** (**IDS**) is a device or software application that monitors a network or systems for malicious activity or policy violations.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Any intrusion activity or violation is typically either reported to an administrator or collected centrally using a security information and event management (SIEM) system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] A SIEM system combines outputs from multiple sources and uses alarm filtering techniques to distinguish malicious activity from false alarms.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IDS types range in scope from single computers to large networks.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The most common classifications are **network intrusion detection systems** (**NIDS**) and **host-based intrusion detection systems** (**HIDS**).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] A system that monitors important operating system files is an example of an HIDS, while a system that analyzes incoming network traffic is an example of an NIDS.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It is also possible to classify IDS by detection approach.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The most well-known variants are signature-based detection (recognizing bad patterns, such as exploitation attempts) and anomaly-based detection (detecting deviations from a model of "good" traffic, which often relies on machine learning).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Another common variant is reputation-based detection (recognizing the potential threat according to the reputation scores).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Some IDS products have the ability to respond to detected intrusions.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Systems with response capabilities are typically referred to as an **intrusion prevention system** (**IPS**).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection systems can also serve specific purposes by augmenting them with custom tools, such as using a honeypot to attract and characterize malicious traffic.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Although they both relate to network security, an IDS differs from a firewall in that a conventional network firewall (distinct from a next-generation firewall) uses a static set of rules to permit or deny network connections.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It implicitly prevents intrusions, assuming an appropriate set of rules have been defined.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Essentially, firewalls limit access between networks to prevent intrusion and do not signal an attack from inside the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS describes a suspected intrusion once it has taken place and signals an alarm.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS also watches for attacks that originate from within a system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This is traditionally achieved by examining network communications, identifying heuristics and patterns (often known as signatures) of common computer attacks, and taking action to alert operators.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] A system that terminates connections is called an intrusion prevention system, and performs access control like an application layer firewall.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IDS can be classified by where detection takes place (network or host) or the detection method that is employed (signature or anomaly-based).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Network intrusion detection systems (NIDS) are placed at a strategic point or points within the network to monitor traffic to and from all devices on the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It performs an analysis of passing traffic on the entire subnet, and matches the traffic that is passed on the subnets to the library of known attacks.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Once an attack is identified, or abnormal behavior is sensed, the alert can be sent to the administrator.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS function to safeguard every device and the entire network from unauthorized access.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An example of an NIDS would be installing it on the subnet where firewalls are located in order to see if someone is trying to break into the firewall.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Ideally one would scan all inbound and outbound traffic, however doing so might create a bottleneck that would impair the overall speed of the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] OPNET and NetSim are commonly used tools for simulating network intrusion detection systems.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] NID Systems are also capable of comparing signatures for similar packets to link and drop harmful detected packets which have a signature matching the records in the NIDS.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] When we classify the design of the NIDS according to the system interactivity property, there are two types: on-line and off-line NIDS, often referred to as inline and tap mode, respectively.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] On-line NIDS deals with the network in real time.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It analyses the Ethernet packets and applies some rules, to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Off-line NIDS deals with stored data and passes it through some processes to decide if it is an attack or not.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] NIDS can be also combined with other technologies to increase detection and prediction rates.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Artificial Neural Network (ANN) based IDS are capable of analyzing huge volumes of data due to the hidden layers and non-linear modeling, however this process requires time due its complex structure.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This allows IDS to more efficiently recognize intrusion patterns.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Neural networks assist IDS in predicting attacks by learning from mistakes; ANN based IDS help develop an early warning system, based on two layers.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The first layer accepts single values, while the second layer takes the first's layers output as input; the cycle repeats and allows the system to automatically recognize new unforeseen patterns in the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This system can average 99.9% detection and classification rate, based on research results of 24 network attacks, divided in four categories: DOS, Probe, Remote-to-Local, and user-to-root.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Host intrusion detection systems (HIDS) run on individual hosts or devices on the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] A HIDS monitors the inbound and outbound packets from the device only and will alert the user or administrator if suspicious activity is detected.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It takes a snapshot of existing system files and matches it to the previous snapshot.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] If the critical system files were modified or deleted, an alert is sent to the administrator to investigate.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An example of HIDS usage can be seen on mission critical machines, which are not expected to change their configurations.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Signature-based IDS is the detection of attacks by looking for specific patterns, such as byte sequences in network traffic, or known malicious instruction sequences used by malware.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This terminology originates from anti-virus software, which refers to these detected patterns as signatures.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Although signature-based IDS can easily detect known attacks, it is difficult to detect new attacks, for which no pattern is available.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In signature-based IDS, the signatures are released by a vendor for all its products.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] On-time updating of the IDS with the signature is a key aspect.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Anomaly-based intrusion detection systems were primarily introduced to detect unknown attacks, in part due to the rapid development of malware.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The basic approach is to use machine learning to create a model of trustworthy activity, and then compare new behavior against this model.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Since these models can be trained according to the applications and hardware configurations, machine learning based method has a better generalized property in comparison to traditional signature-based IDS.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Although this approach enables the detection of previously unknown attacks, it may suffer from false positives: previously unknown legitimate activity may also be classified as malicious.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Most of the existing IDSs suffer from the time-consuming during detection process that degrades the performance of IDSs.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Efficient feature selection algorithm makes the classification process used in detection more reliable.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Recent research has also explored deep learning approaches for anomaly-based intrusion detection, as these methods can learn complex traffic patterns and help identify previously unseen attacks more effectively.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] New types of what could be called anomaly-based intrusion detection systems are being viewed by Gartner as User and Entity Behavior Analytics (UEBA) (an evolution of the user behavior analytics category) and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In particular, NTA deals with malicious insiders as well as targeted external attacks that have compromised a user machine or account.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Gartner has noted that some organizations have opted for NTA over more traditional IDS.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Some systems may attempt to stop an intrusion attempt but this is neither required nor expected of a monitoring system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion detection and prevention systems (IDPS) are primarily focused on identifying possible incidents, logging information about them, and reporting attempts.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In addition, organizations use IDPS for other purposes, such as identifying problems with security policies, documenting existing threats and deterring individuals from violating security policies.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS have become a necessary addition to the security infrastructure of nearly every organization.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IDPS typically record information related to observed events, notify security administrators of important observed events and produce reports.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Many IDPS can also respond to a detected threat by attempting to prevent it from succeeding.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] They use several response techniques, which involve the IDPS stopping the attack itself, changing the security environment (e.g. reconfiguring a firewall) or changing the attack's content.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Intrusion prevention systems are considered extensions of intrusion detection systems because they both monitor network traffic and/or system activities for malicious activity.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The main differences are, unlike intrusion detection systems, intrusion prevention systems are placed in-line and are able to actively prevent or block intrusions that are detected.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IPS can take such actions as sending an alarm, dropping detected malicious packets, resetting a connection or blocking traffic from the offending IP address.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An IPS also can correct cyclic redundancy check (CRC) errors, defragment packet streams, mitigate TCP sequencing issues, and clean up unwanted transport and network layer options.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] **Wireless intrusion prevention system (WIPS)**: monitor a wireless network for suspicious traffic by analyzing wireless networking protocols.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] **Network behavior analysis (NBA)**: examines network traffic to identify threats that generate unusual traffic flows, such as distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks, certain forms of malware and policy violations.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] **Host-based intrusion prevention system (HIPS)**: an installed software package which monitors a single host for suspicious activity by analyzing events occurring within that host.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The majority of intrusion prevention systems utilize one of three detection methods: signature-based, statistical anomaly-based, and stateful protocol analysis.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] **Statistical anomaly-based detection**: An IDS which is anomaly-based will monitor network traffic and compare it against an established baseline.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The baseline will identify what is "normal" for that network – what sort of bandwidth is generally used and what protocols are used.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It may however, raise a False Positive alarm for legitimate use of bandwidth if the baselines are not intelligently configured.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Ensemble models that use Matthews correlation co-efficient to identify unauthorized network traffic have obtained 99.73% accuracy.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] **Stateful protocol analysis detection**: This method identifies deviations of protocol states by comparing observed events with "pre-determined profiles of generally accepted definitions of benign activity".
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] While it is capable of knowing and tracing the protocol states, it requires significant resources.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The correct placement of intrusion detection systems is critical and varies depending on the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The most common placement is behind the firewall, on the edge of a network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This practice provides the IDS with high visibility of traffic entering your network and will not receive any traffic between users on the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The edge of the network is the point in which a network connects to the extranet.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] If an IDS is placed beyond a network's firewall, its main purpose would be to defend against noise from the internet but, more importantly, defend against common attacks, such as port scans and network mapper.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] An IDS in this position would monitor layers 4 through 7 of the OSI model and would be signature-based.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] This is a very useful practice, because rather than showing actual breaches into the network that made it through the firewall, attempted breaches will be shown which reduces the amount of false positives.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The IDS in this position also assists in decreasing the amount of time it takes to discover successful attacks against a network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Sometimes an IDS with more advanced features will be integrated with a firewall in order to be able to intercept sophisticated attacks entering the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Examples of advanced features would include multiple security contexts in the routing level and bridging mode.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] All of this in turn potentially reduces cost and operational complexity.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Another option for IDS placement is within the actual network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] These will reveal attacks or suspicious activity within the network.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Ignoring the security within a network can cause many problems, it will either allow users to bring about security risks or allow an attacker who has already broken into the network to roam around freely.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Intense intranet security makes it difficult for even those hackers within the network to maneuver around and escalate their privileges.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The earliest preliminary IDS concept was delineated in 1980 by James Anderson at the National Security Agency and consisted of a set of tools intended to help administrators review audit trails.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] User access logs, file access logs, and system event logs are examples of audit trails.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Fred Cohen noted in 1987 that it is impossible to detect an intrusion in every case, and that the resources needed to detect intrusions grow with the amount of usage.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Neumann, published a model of an IDS in 1986 that formed the basis for many systems today.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Her model used statistics for anomaly detection, and resulted in an early IDS at SRI International named the Intrusion Detection Expert System (IDES), which ran on Sun workstations and could consider both user and network level data.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] IDES had a dual approach with a rule-based Expert System to detect known types of intrusions plus a statistical anomaly detection component based on profiles of users, host systems, and target systems.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The author of "IDES: An Intelligent System for Detecting Intruders", Teresa F.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Lunt, proposed adding an artificial neural network as a third component.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] She said all three components could then report to a resolver.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] SRI followed IDES in 1993 with the Next-generation Intrusion Detection Expert System (NIDES).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Multics intrusion detection and alerting system (MIDAS), an expert system using P-BEST and Lisp, was developed in 1988 based on the work of Denning and Neumann.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Haystack was also developed in that year using statistics to reduce audit trails.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In 1986 the National Security Agency started an IDS research transfer program under Rebecca Bace.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Bace later published the seminal text on the subject, *Intrusion Detection*, in 2000.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Wisdom & Sense (W&S) was a statistics-based anomaly detector developed in 1989 at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] W&S created rules based on statistical analysis, and then used those rules for anomaly detection.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In 1990, the Time-based Inductive Machine (TIM) did anomaly detection using inductive learning of sequential user patterns in Common Lisp on a VAX 3500 computer.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Security Monitor (NSM) performed masking on access matrices for anomaly detection on a Sun-3/50 workstation.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Information Security Officer's Assistant (ISOA) was a 1990 prototype that considered a variety of strategies including statistics, a profile checker, and an expert system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] ComputerWatch at AT&T Bell Labs used statistics and rules for audit data reduction and intrusion detection.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Then, in 1991, researchers at the University of California, Davis created a prototype Distributed Intrusion Detection System (DIDS), which was also an expert system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Network Anomaly Detection and Intrusion Reporter (NADIR), also in 1991, was a prototype IDS developed at the Los Alamos National Laboratory's Integrated Computing Network (ICN), and was heavily influenced by the work of Denning and Lunt.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] NADIR used a statistics-based anomaly detector and an expert system.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced Bro in 1998, which used its own rule language for packet analysis from libpcap data.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Network Flight Recorder (NFR) in 1999 also used libpcap.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] APE was developed as a packet sniffer, also using libpcap, in November, 1998, and was renamed Snort one month later.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Snort has since become the world's largest used IDS/IPS system with over 300,000 active users.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] It can monitor both local systems, and remote capture points using the TZSP protocol.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Audit Data Analysis and Mining (ADAM) IDS in 2001 used tcpdump to build profiles of rules for classifications.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In 2003, Yongguang Zhang and Wenke Lee argue for the importance of IDS in networks with mobile nodes.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In 2015, Viegas and his colleagues proposed an anomaly-based intrusion detection engine, aiming System-on-Chip (SoC) for applications in Internet of Things (IoT), for instance.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The proposal applies machine learning for anomaly detection, providing energy-efficiency to a Decision Tree, Naive-Bayes, and k-Nearest Neighbors classifiers implementation in an Atom CPU and its hardware-friendly implementation in a FPGA.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In the literature, this was the first work that implement each classifier equivalently in software and hardware and measures its energy consumption on both.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Additionally, it was the first time that was measured the energy consumption for extracting each features used to make the network packet classification, implemented in software and hardware.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] Several regulatory frameworks require or recommend intrusion detection capabilities as part of information security compliance.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] In the United States, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities to implement procedures for monitoring log-in attempts and reporting discrepancies as part of their information system activity review.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The December 2024 Notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) to overhaul the HIPAA Security Rule would explicitly mandate deployment of intrusion detection and intrusion prevention systems, along with continuous monitoring of all information systems containing electronic protected health information.
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires the use of intrusion detection or intrusion prevention techniques to detect or prevent intrusions into networks handling cardholder data (Requirement 11.5).
[src:snort-ids/intrusion-detection-system] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) SP 800-53 includes the SI-4 (Information System Monitoring) control family, which specifies intrusion detection as a core capability for federal information systems.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] A **packet analyzer** (also **packet sniffer** or **network analyzer**) is a computer program or computer hardware such as a packet capture appliance that can analyze and log traffic that passes over a computer network or part of a network.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] **Packet capture** is the process of intercepting and logging traffic.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] As data streams flow across the network, the analyzer captures each packet and, if needed, decodes the packet's raw data, showing the values of various fields in the packet, and analyzes its content according to the appropriate RFC or other specifications.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] A packet analyzer used for intercepting traffic on wireless networks is known as a **wireless analyzer**—those designed specifically for Wi-Fi networks are **Wi-Fi analyzers**.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] While a packet analyzer can also be referred to as a network analyzer or protocol analyzer, these terms can also have other meanings.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] The class of protocol analyzers can technically be a broader, more general class that includes packet analyzers and sniffers.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] However, the terms are frequently used interchangeably.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] On wired shared-medium networks, such as Ethernet, Token Ring, and FDDI, depending on the network structure (hub or switch), it may be possible to capture all traffic on the network from a single machine.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] On modern networks, traffic can be captured using a network switch using port mirroring, which mirrors all packets that pass through designated ports of the switch to another port, if the switch supports port mirroring.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] A network tap is an even more reliable solution than using a monitoring port since taps are less likely to drop packets during high traffic loads.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, traffic can be captured on one channel at a time, or by using multiple adapters, on several channels simultaneously.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] On wired broadcast and wireless LANs, to capture unicast traffic between other machines, the network adapter capturing the traffic must be in promiscuous mode.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, even if the adapter is in promiscuous mode, packets not for the service set the adapter is configured for are usually ignored.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] To see those packets, the adapter must be in monitor mode.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] No special provisions are required to capture multicast traffic to a multicast group the packet analyzer is already monitoring, or broadcast traffic.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] When traffic is captured, either the entire contents of packets or just the headers are recorded.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Recording just headers reduces storage requirements and avoids some privacy legal issues, yet often provides sufficient information to diagnose problems.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Captured information is decoded from raw digital form into a human-readable format that lets engineers review exchanged information.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers vary in their abilities to display and analyze data.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Some packet analyzers can also generate traffic.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Such testers generate protocol-correct traffic for functional testing, and may also have the ability to deliberately introduce errors to test the device under test's ability to handle errors.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers can also be hardware-based, either in probe format or, as is increasingly common, combined with a disk array.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] These devices record packets or packet headers to a disk array.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Packet capture can be used to fulfill a warrant from a law enforcement agency to wiretap all network traffic generated by an individual.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Internet service providers and VoIP providers in the United States must comply with Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act regulations.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Using packet capture and storage, telecommunications carriers can provide the legally required secure and separate access to targeted network traffic and can use the same device for internal security purposes.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] Collecting data from a carrier system without a warrant is illegal due to laws about interception.
[src:snort-ids/packet-analyzer] By using end-to-end encryption, communications can be kept confidential from telecommunication carriers and legal authorities.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software was originally developed to detect and remove computer viruses, hence the name.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, with the proliferation of other malware, antivirus software started to protect against other computer threats.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some products also include protection from malicious URLs, spam, and phishing.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The first known computer virus appeared in 1971 and was dubbed the "Creeper virus".
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This computer virus infected Digital Equipment Corporation's (DEC) PDP-10 mainframe computers running the TENEX operating system.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The Creeper virus was eventually deleted by a program created by Ray Tomlinson and known as "The Reaper".
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some people consider "The Reaper" the first antivirus software ever written – it may be the case, but the Reaper was actually a virus itself specifically designed to remove the Creeper virus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The Creeper virus was followed by several other viruses.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The first known that appeared "in the wild" was "Elk Cloner", in 1981, which infected Apple II computers.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1983, the term *"computer virus"* was coined by Fred Cohen in one of the first ever published academic papers on computer viruses.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The first IBM PC compatible "in the wild" computer virus, and one of the first real widespread infections, was "Brain" in 1986.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] From then, the number of viruses has grown exponentially.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Most of the computer viruses written in the early and mid-1980s were limited to self-reproduction and had no specific damage routine built into the code.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] That changed when more and more programmers became acquainted with computer virus programming and created viruses that manipulated or even destroyed data on infected computers.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Before internet connectivity was widespread, computer viruses were typically spread by infected floppy disks.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software came into use, but was updated relatively infrequently.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] During this time, virus checkers essentially had to check executable files and the boot sectors of floppy disks and hard disks.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, as internet usage became common, viruses began to spread online.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] There are competing claims for the innovator of the first antivirus product.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Possibly, the first publicly documented removal of an "in the wild" computer virus (the "Vienna virus") was performed by Bernd Fix in 1987.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1985, in United Kingdom, Jan Hruska and Peter Lammer founded the security firm Sophos and began producing their first antivirus and encryption products.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In the same period, in Hungary, VirusBuster was founded (and subsequently incorporated by Sophos).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1987, Andreas Lüning and Kai Figge, who founded G Data Software in 1985, released their first antivirus product for the Atari ST platform.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1987, the *Ultimate Virus Killer (UVK)* was also released.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This was the de facto industry standard virus killer for the Atari ST and Atari Falcon, the last version of which (version 9.0) was released in April 2004.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1987, in the United States, John McAfee founded the McAfee company and, at the end of that year, he released the first version of VirusScan.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Also in 1987 (in Czechoslovakia), Peter Paško, Rudolf Hrubý, and Miroslav Trnka created the first version of NOD antivirus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1987, Fred Cohen wrote that *there is no algorithm that can perfectly detect all possible computer viruses*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Finally, at the end of 1987, the first two heuristic antivirus utilities were released: *Flushot Plus* by Ross Greenberg and *Anti4us* by Erwin Lanting.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, the kind of heuristic used by early AV engines was totally different from those used today.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The first product with a heuristic engine resembling modern ones was F-PROT in 1991.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Early heuristic engines were based on dividing the binary into different sections: data section, code section (in a legitimate binary, it usually starts always from the same location).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Indeed, the initial viruses re-organized the layout of the sections, or overrode the initial portion of a section in order to jump to the very end of the file where malicious code was located—only going back to resume execution of the original code.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This was a very specific pattern, not used at the time by any legitimate software, which represented an elegant heuristic to catch suspicious code.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Other kinds of more advanced heuristics were later added, such as suspicious section names, incorrect header size, regular expressions, and partial pattern in-memory matching.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1988, the growth of antivirus companies continued.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In Germany, Tjark Auerbach founded Avira (*H+BEDV* at the time) and released the first version of *AntiVir* (named *"Luke Filewalker"* at the time).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In Spain, Carlos Jiménez released the first version of his antivirus (he founded Anyware Seguridad Informática, now part of McAfee, one year later).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In Bulgaria, Vesselin Bontchev released his first freeware antivirus program (he later joined FRISK Software).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Also Frans Veldman released the first version of ThunderByte Antivirus, also known as *TBAV* (he sold his company to Norman Safeground in 1998).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In Czechoslovakia, Pavel Baudiš and Eduard Kučera founded Avast Software (at the time *ALWIL Software*) and released their first version of avast! antivirus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In June 1988, in South Korea, Ahn Cheol-Soo released its first antivirus software, called *V1* (he founded AhnLab later in 1995).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Finally, in autumn 1988, in the United Kingdom, Alan Solomon founded S&S International and created his *Dr.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Solomon's Anti-Virus Toolkit* (although he launched it commercially only in 1991 – in 1998 Solomon's company was acquired by McAfee, then known as Network Associates Inc.).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Also in 1988, a mailing list named VIRUS-L was started on the BITNET/EARN network where new viruses and the possibilities of detecting and eliminating viruses were discussed.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some members of this mailing list were: Alan Solomon, Eugene Kaspersky (Kaspersky Lab), Friðrik Skúlason (FRISK Software), John McAfee (McAfee), Luis Corrons (Panda Security), Mikko Hyppönen (F-Secure), Péter Szőr, Tjark Auerbach (Avira) and Vesselin Bontchev (FRISK Software).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1989, in Iceland, Friðrik Skúlason created the first version of F-PROT Anti-Virus (he founded FRISK Software only in 1993).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Meanwhile, in the United States, Symantec (founded by Gary Hendrix in 1982) launched its first *Symantec antivirus for Macintosh* (SAM).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] SAM 2.0, released March 1990, incorporated technology allowing users to easily update SAM to intercept and eliminate new viruses, including many that didn't exist at the time of the program's release.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1990, in Spain, Mikel Urizarbarrena founded Panda Security (*Panda Software* at the time).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In Hungary, the security researcher Péter Szőr released the first version of *Pasteur* antivirus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1990, the Computer Antivirus Research Organization (CARO) was founded.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1991, CARO released the *"Virus Naming Scheme"*, originally written by Friðrik Skúlason and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Although this naming scheme is now outdated, it remains the only existing standard that most computer security companies and researchers ever attempted to adopt.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] CARO members includes: Alan Solomon, Costin Raiu, Dmitry Gryaznov, Eugene Kaspersky, Friðrik Skúlason, Igor Muttik, Mikko Hyppönen, Morton Swimmer, Nick FitzGerald, Padgett Peterson, Peter Ferrie, Righard Zwienenberg and Vesselin Bontchev.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1991, in the United States, Symantec released the first version of Norton AntiVirus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] On the other hand, in Finland, F-Secure (founded in 1988 by Petri Allas and Risto Siilasmaa – with the name of Data Fellows) released the first version of their antivirus product.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] F-Secure claims to be the first antivirus firm to establish a presence on the World Wide Web.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1991, the European Institute for Computer Antivirus Research (EICAR) was founded to further antivirus research and improve development of antivirus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1992, in Russia, Igor Danilov released the first version of *SpiderWeb*, which later became Dr.Web.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1994, AV-TEST reported that there were 28,613 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1996, in Romania, Bitdefender was founded and released the first version of *Anti-Virus eXpert* (AVX).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1997, in Russia, Eugene Kaspersky and Natalya Kaspersky co-founded security firm Kaspersky Lab.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1996, there was also the first "in the wild" Linux virus, known as *"Staog"*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 1999, AV-TEST reported that there were 98,428 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2000, Rainer Link and Howard Fuhs started the first open source antivirus engine, called *OpenAntivirus Project*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2001, Tomasz Kojm released the first version of ClamAV, the first ever open source antivirus engine to be commercialised.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2007, ClamAV was bought by Sourcefire, which in turn was acquired by Cisco Systems in 2013.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2002, in United Kingdom, Morten Lund and Theis Søndergaard co-founded the antivirus firm BullGuard.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2005, AV-TEST reported that there were 333,425 unique malware samples (based on MD5) in their database.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2007, AV-TEST reported a number of 5,490,960 new unique malware samples (based on MD5) only for that year.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2012 and 2013, antivirus firms reported a new malware samples range from 300,000 to over 500,000 per day.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2005, F-Secure was the first security firm that developed an Anti-Rootkit technology, called *BlackLight*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Because most users are usually connected to the Internet on a continual basis, Jon Oberheide first proposed a Cloud-based antivirus design in 2008.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In February 2008 McAfee Labs added the industry-first cloud-based anti-malware functionality to VirusScan under the name Artemis.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] It was tested by AV-Comparatives in February 2008 and officially unveiled in August 2008 in McAfee VirusScan.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Cloud AV created problems for comparative testing of security software – part of the AV definitions was out of testers control (on constantly updated AV company servers) thus making results non-repeatable.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] As a result, Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organisation (AMTSO) started working on method of testing cloud products which was adopted on May 7, 2009.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2011, AVG introduced a similar cloud service, called Protective Cloud Technology.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Following the 2013 release of the APT 1 report from Mandiant, the industry has seen a shift towards signature-less approaches to the problem capable of detecting and mitigating zero-day attacks.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Numerous approaches to address these new forms of threats have appeared, including behavioral detection, artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cloud-based file detection.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] According to Gartner, it is expected the rise of new entrants, such Carbon Black, Cylance and Crowdstrike will force end point protection incumbents into a new phase of innovation and acquisition.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] One method from Bromium involves micro-virtualization to protect desktops from malicious code execution initiated by the end user.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Another approach from SentinelOne and Carbon Black focuses on behavioral detection by building a full context around every process execution path in real time, while Cylance leverages an artificial intelligence model based on machine learning.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Increasingly, these signature-less approaches have been defined by the media and analyst firms as "next-generation" antivirus and are seeing rapid market adoption as certified antivirus replacement technologies by firms such as Coalfire and DirectDefense.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In response, traditional antivirus vendors such as Trend Micro, Symantec and Sophos have responded by incorporating "next-gen" offerings into their portfolios as analyst firms such as Forrester and Gartner have called traditional signature-based antivirus "ineffective" and "outdated".
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] As of Windows 8, Windows includes its own free antivirus protection under the Windows Defender brand.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Despite bad detection scores in its early days, AV-Test now certifies Defender as one of its top products.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] While it isn't publicly known how the inclusion of antivirus software in Windows affected antivirus sales, Google search traffic for antivirus has declined significantly since 2010.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Since 2016, there has been a notable amount of consolidation in the industry.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Avast purchased AVG in 2016 for $1.3 billion.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Avira was acquired by Norton owner Gen Digital (then NortonLifeLock) in 2020 for $360 million.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2021, the Avira division of Gen Digital acquired BullGuard.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The BullGuard brand was discontinued in 2022 and its customers were migrated to Norton.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2022, Gen Digital acquired Avast, effectively consolidating four major antivirus brands under one owner.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In September 2024, following the US Commerce Department's ban on Kaspersky, Pango Group acquired its customers (about 1 million).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The customers received continued services with no action required on their part.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Then, in December 2024, Pango Group merged with Total Security, the provider of Total AV antivirus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The combined entity, now called Point Wild, has an enterprise value of $1.7 billion.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] As of 2024, more than half of Americans use built-in antivirus protection for their devices like Microsoft Defender or XProtect from Apple.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, about 121 million adults still use third-party antivirus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Half of these adults use paid products, and about 50% of third-party software users - the owners of personal computers and Windows operating systems.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus programs on mobile devices are used by 17% of adults.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The 2025 antivirus market report confirms that most third-party antivirus users are on desktop devices, primarily aged between 35 and 45.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In contrast, younger users (18–25) tend to rely on ad blockers instead.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In the U.S., on average, 75–85% of people use antivirus software or some other form of protection on at least one device.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software for computers and mobile devices is predominantly used by residents of large cities.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Mobile device users more often rely on password managers rather than antivirus software for digital security.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Moreover, the majority of password‑manager users live in medium‑sized and small towns.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Cohen demonstrated that the algorithm which would be able to detect all possible viruses can't possibly exist (like the algorithm which determines whether or not the given program halts).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, using different layers of defense, a good detection rate may be achieved.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Traditional antivirus software relies heavily upon signatures to identify malware.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Substantially, when a malware sample arrives in the hands of an antivirus firm, it is analysed by malware researchers or by dynamic analysis systems.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Then, once it is determined to be a malware, a proper signature of the file is extracted and added to the signatures database of the antivirus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Many viruses start as a single infection and through either mutation or refinements by other attackers, can grow into dozens of slightly different strains, called variants.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Generic detection refers to the detection and removal of multiple threats using a single virus definition.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] For example, the Vundo trojan has several family members, depending on the antivirus vendor's classification.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Symantec classifies members of the Vundo family into two distinct categories, *Trojan.Vundo* and *Trojan.Vundo.B*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] While it may be advantageous to identify a specific virus, it can be quicker to detect a virus family through a generic signature or through an inexact match to an existing signature.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Virus researchers find common areas that all viruses in a family share uniquely and can thus create a single generic signature.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] These signatures often contain non-contiguous code, using wildcard characters where differences lie.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] These wildcards allow the scanner to detect viruses even if they are padded with extra, meaningless code.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A detection that uses this method is said to be "heuristic detection".
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can attempt to scan for rootkits.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A rootkit is a type of malware designed to gain administrative-level control over a computer system without being detected.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Rootkits can change how the operating system functions and in some cases can tamper with the anti-virus program and render it ineffective.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Rootkits are also difficult to remove, in some cases requiring a complete re-installation of the operating system.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Real-time protection, on-access scanning, background guard, resident shield, autoprotect, and other synonyms refer to the automatic protection provided by most antivirus, anti-spyware, and other anti-malware programs.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This monitors computer systems for suspicious activity such as computer viruses, spyware, adware, and other malicious objects.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Real-time protection detects threats in opened files and scans apps in real-time as they are installed on the device.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] When inserting a CD, opening an email, or browsing the web, or when a file already on the computer is opened or executed.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Machine learning has emerged as a core detection method in modern antivirus software, using algorithms trained on large datasets to classify software as malicious or benign.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] ML-based approaches are diverse, but detectors typically extract features from files, such as API call sequences, byte n-grams, opcode distributions, behavioral characteristics, or even raw bytes, and train classifiers to identify malware based on learned patterns from this data.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] ML-based detection can be highly effective, but still faces significant challenges.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Concept drift occurs as malware continuously evolves, causing trained models to degrade in accuracy over time without regular retraining on fresh samples.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Research has demonstrated that even simple obfuscation techniques can create adversarial variants that bypass ML-based detectors while preserving malicious functionality.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Additionally, the highly imbalanced nature of real-world data, where benign files vastly outnumber malicious ones, makes acquiring training data difficult and requires careful tuning to avoid unacceptable false positive rates.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some commercial antivirus software end-user license agreements include a clause that the subscription will be automatically renewed, and the purchaser's credit card automatically billed, at the renewal time without explicit approval.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] For example, McAfee requires users to unsubscribe at least 60 days before the expiration of the present subscription, while Bitdefender sends notifications to unsubscribe 30 days before the renewal.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Norton AntiVirus also renews subscriptions automatically by default.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some apparent antivirus programs are actually malware masquerading as legitimate software, such as WinFixer, MS Antivirus, and Mac Defender.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A "false positive" or "false alarm" is when antivirus software identifies a non-malicious file as malware.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] When this happens, it can cause serious problems.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] For example, if an antivirus program is configured to immediately delete or quarantine infected files, as is common on Microsoft Windows antivirus applications, a false positive in an essential file can render the Windows operating system or some applications unusable.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Recovering from such damage to critical software infrastructure incurs technical support costs and businesses can be forced to close whilst remedial action is undertaken.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Running (the real-time protection of) multiple antivirus programs concurrently can degrade performance and create conflicts.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, using a concept called multiscanning, several companies (including G Data Software and Microsoft) have created applications which can run multiple engines concurrently.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] It is sometimes necessary to temporarily disable virus protection when installing major updates such as Windows Service Packs or updating graphics card drivers.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Active antivirus protection may partially or completely prevent the installation of a major update.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can cause problems during the installation of an operating system upgrade, e.g. when upgrading to a newer version of Windows "in place"—without erasing the previous version of Windows.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Microsoft recommends that anti-virus software be disabled to avoid conflicts with the upgrade installation process.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Active anti-virus software can also interfere with a firmware update process.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The functionality of a few computer programs can be hampered by active anti-virus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] For example, TrueCrypt, a disk encryption program, states on its troubleshooting page that anti-virus programs can conflict with TrueCrypt and cause it to malfunction or operate very slowly.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software can impair the performance and stability of games running in the Steam platform.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Support issues also exist around antivirus application interoperability with common solutions like SSL VPN remote access and network access control products.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] These technology solutions often have policy assessment applications that require an up-to-date antivirus to be installed and running.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] If the antivirus application is not recognized by the policy assessment, whether because the antivirus application has been updated or because it is not part of the policy assessment library, the user will be unable to connect.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Studies in December 2007 showed that the effectiveness of antivirus software had decreased in the previous year, particularly against unknown or zero day attacks.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The computer magazine *c't* found that detection rates for these threats had dropped from 40 to 50% in 2006 to 20–30% in 2007.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] At that time, the only exception was the NOD32 antivirus, which managed a detection rate of 68%.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] According to the *ZeuS tracker* website the average detection rate for all variants of the ZeuS trojan is as low as 40%.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The problem is magnified by the changing intent of virus authors.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some years ago it was obvious when a virus infection was present.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] At the time, viruses were written by amateurs and exhibited destructive behavior or pop-ups.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Modern viruses are often written by professionals, financed by criminal organizations.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2008, Eva Chen, CEO of Trend Micro, stated that the anti-virus industry has over-hyped how effective its products are—and so has been misleading customers—for years.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Independent testing on all the major virus scanners consistently shows that none provides 100% virus detection.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The best ones provided as high as 99.9% detection for simulated real-world situations, while the lowest provided 91.1% in tests conducted in August 2013.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Many virus scanners produce false positive results as well, identifying benign files as malware.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Although methods may differ, some notable independent quality testing agencies include AV-Comparatives, ICSA Labs, SE Labs, West Coast Labs, *Virus Bulletin*, AV-TEST and other members of the Anti-Malware Testing Standards Organization.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus programs are not always effective against new viruses, even those that use non-signature-based methods that should detect new viruses.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The reason for this is that the virus designers test their new viruses on the major anti-virus applications to make sure that they are not detected before releasing them into the wild.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some new viruses, particularly ransomware, use polymorphic code to avoid detection by virus scanners.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A proof of concept virus has used the Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) to avoid detection from anti-virus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The potential success of this involves bypassing the CPU in order to make it much harder for security researchers to analyse the inner workings of such malware.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Detecting rootkits is a major challenge for anti-virus programs.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Rootkits have full administrative access to the computer and are invisible to users and hidden from the list of running processes in the task manager.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Rootkits can modify the inner workings of the operating system and tamper with antivirus programs.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] If a file has been infected by a computer virus, anti-virus software will attempt to remove the virus code from the file during disinfection, but it is not always able to restore the file to its undamaged state.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In such circumstances, damaged files can only be restored from existing backups or shadow copies (this is also true for ransomware); installed software that is damaged requires re-installation (however, see System File Checker).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Any writeable firmware in the computer can be infected by malicious code.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This is a major concern, as an infected BIOS could require the actual BIOS chip to be replaced to ensure the malicious code is completely removed.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software is not effective at protecting firmware and the motherboard BIOS from infection.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] In 2014, security researchers discovered that USB devices contain writeable firmware which can be modified with malicious code (dubbed "BadUSB"), which anti-virus software cannot detect or prevent.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The malicious code can run undetected on the computer and could even infect the operating system prior to it booting up.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software has some drawbacks, first of which that it can impact a computer's performance.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Furthermore, inexperienced users can be lulled into a false sense of security when using the computer, considering their computers to be invulnerable, and may have problems understanding the prompts and decisions that antivirus software presents them with.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] An incorrect decision may lead to a security breach.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] If the antivirus software employs heuristic detection, it must be fine-tuned to minimize misidentifying harmless software as malicious (false positive).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software itself usually runs at the highly trusted kernel level of the operating system to allow it access to all the potential malicious process and files, creating a potential avenue of attack.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] The US National Security Agency (NSA) and the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ) intelligence agencies, respectively, have been exploiting anti-virus software to spy on users.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Anti-virus software has highly privileged and trusted access to the underlying operating system, which makes it a much more appealing target for remote attacks.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Additionally anti-virus software is "years behind security-conscious client-side applications like browsers or document readers.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] It means that Acrobat Reader, Microsoft Word or Google Chrome are harder to exploit than 90 percent of the anti-virus products out there", according to Joxean Koret, a researcher with Coseinc, a Singapore-based information security consultancy.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Antivirus software running on individual computers is the most common method employed of guarding against malware, but it is not the only solution.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Other solutions can also be employed by users, including Unified Threat Management (UTM), hardware and network firewalls, Cloud-based antivirus, online scanners, and Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR).
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Network firewalls prevent unknown programs and processes from accessing the system.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] However, they are not antivirus systems and make no attempt to identify or remove anything.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] They may protect against infection from outside the protected computer or network, and limit the activity of any malicious software which is present by blocking incoming or outgoing requests on certain TCP/IP ports.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A firewall is designed to deal with broader system threats that come from network connections into the system and is not an alternative to a virus protection system.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Cloud antivirus is a technology that uses lightweight agent software on the protected computer, while offloading the majority of data analysis to the provider's infrastructure.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] One approach to implementing cloud antivirus involves scanning suspicious files using multiple antivirus engines.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This approach was proposed by an early implementation of the cloud antivirus concept called CloudAV.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] CloudAV was designed to send programs or documents to a network cloud where multiple antivirus and behavioral detection programs are used simultaneously in order to improve detection rates.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Parallel scanning of files using potentially incompatible antivirus scanners is achieved by spawning a virtual machine per detection engine and therefore eliminating any possible issues.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] CloudAV can also perform "retrospective detection", whereby the cloud detection engine rescans all files in its file access history when a new threat is identified thus improving new threat detection speed.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Finally, CloudAV is a solution for effective virus scanning on devices that lack the computing power to perform the scans themselves.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some examples of cloud anti-virus products are Panda Cloud Antivirus and Immunet.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Comodo Group has also produced cloud-based anti-virus.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Some antivirus vendors maintain websites with free online scanning capability of the entire computer, critical areas only, local disks, folders or files.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Periodic online scanning is a good idea for those that run antivirus applications on their computers because those applications are frequently slow to catch threats.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] One of the first things that malicious software does in an attack is disable any existing antivirus software and sometimes the only way to know of an attack is by turning to an online resource that is not installed on the infected computer.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Content Disarm & Reconstruction (CDR) technology protects a network from malware by removing components from inbound files which do not rigorously conform with the standards of that file type.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] It does so by rebuilding the original files without any illegitimate components present.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Part of the CDR process may also involve flattening and converting the reconstructed files to Portable Document Format (PDF) for maximum safety.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] CDR malware removal does not attempt to identify malware behavior before taking action; rather, it employs a zero-trust approach against files entering a network perimeter.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] This can make it an effective solution for protecting networks against zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Virus removal tools are available to help remove stubborn infections or a certain type of infection.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Examples include *Windows Malicious Software Removal Tool*, *Kaspersky Virus Removal Tool*, and *Sophos Scan & Clean*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] It is also worth noting that sometimes antivirus software can produce a false-positive result, indicating an infection where there is none.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A rescue disk that is bootable, such as a CD or USB storage device, can be used to run antivirus software outside of the installed operating system in order to remove infections while they are dormant.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A bootable rescue disk can be useful when, for example, the installed operating system is no longer bootable or has malware that is resisting all attempts to be removed by the installed antivirus software.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] Examples of software that can be used on a bootable rescue disk include the *Kaspersky Rescue Disk*, *Trend Micro Rescue Disk*, and *Comodo Rescue Disk*.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] According to an FBI survey, major businesses lose $12 million annually dealing with virus incidents.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] A survey by Symantec in 2009 found that a third of small to medium-sized business did not use antivirus protection at that time, whereas more than 80% of home users had some kind of antivirus installed.
[src:snort-ids/signature-based-detection] According to a sociological survey conducted by G Data Software in 2010 49% of women did not use any antivirus program at all.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] In 2009, Snort entered InfoWorld's Open Source Hall of Fame as one of the "greatest [pieces of] open source software of all time".
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] Snort's open-source network-based intrusion detection/prevention system (IDS/IPS) has the ability to perform real-time traffic analysis and packet logging on Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] Snort performs protocol analysis, content searching and matching.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] The program can also be used to detect probes or attacks, including, but not limited to, operating system fingerprinting attempts, semantic URL attacks, buffer overflows, server message block probes, and stealth port scans.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] Snort can be configured in three main modes: 1. sniffer, 2. packet logger, and 3. network intrusion detection.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] The program will read network packets and display them on the console.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] In packet logger mode, the program will log packets to the disk.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] In intrusion detection mode, the program will monitor network traffic and analyze it against a rule set defined by the user.
[src:snort-ids/snort-software] The program will then perform a specific action based on what has been identified.
